snippet.textDisplay: Julia Child grew up privileged, but always seemed determined to have life on her own terms.  She was denied the military career she craved, but ended up becoming an OSS agent and married another OSS agent.  Her husband was stationed in the Paris embassy and she really learnt to cook in France...and it was a love affair.  She came back to the states and single-handedly popularised haut french cuisine and many basic, provincial cooking techniques to American audiences.  She was--literally--the first 'French' chef most American housewives and families met.  Her books swept the best-seller lists and she was a household name.  Everyone since then owes her a tremendous debt whether or not they know it.  Even later TV cooking shows in early 1970s ( the Galloping Gourmet, The Frugal Gourmet, etc. ) were largely made possible through her efforts.  Early British TV cookery shows aired when TV was young, were brief and didn't reach very many homes.  TV began blossoming and entering its Golden Age just in time for Julia Child to take it by storm.
